"The blow came in 1973 when all Blackhawks were moved to the large frame originally built to contain the pressures of the .44 Magnum.  Now all Blackhawks—whether .44 Magnum, .45 Colt, or .357 Magnum—would be built on this hulking frame.

The larger frame was obviously needed to safely chamber the .44 Magnum, and the .45 Colt certainly benefited from the larger frame size as it essentially became a .45 Colt Magnum.  But the poor .357, one of the most ideal rounds for packing into the woods, receives no benefit from the larger frame at all."

 The simple answer.. Someone who is tired of your shit..

Here's the story:
We schedule a time and place to meet, I'm 10min early (like respectable armslisters are) He texts me only after I have told him I'm in the meeting spot to tell me he's 30min late.. then calls and hangs up on me..

texts me the next day like nothing happens and asks to meet again.. I ignore him..  

Month later he tries again, I had cooled down and figured I'd just get rid of him..
several text messages and an attempted phone call.....you guessed it...nothing..

since January-
7 emails
23 texts 
2-3 phone calls

This guy is the crazy ex-girlfriend of the gun world..

Ballistic vests use layers of very strong fiber to "catch" and deform a bullet, mushrooming it into a dish shape, and spreading its force over a larger portion of the vest fiber. title: For Sale:   ON HOLD - Winchester Model 1897- takedown - 12 Gauge 30" Full Choke
location: St Mary's County, Maryland, United States
postcontent:
Very nice, older but working Winchester 1897. Takedown, 12 Gauge, full choke 30" Barrel, original sights.

Additional pictures at: http://s1166.photobucket.com/user/coj0nes/library/1897%20Winchester   and available upon request. Pictures of trench gun are for past conversion work history. This listing is relative to the 30" takedown Winchester 1897. Sorry for the clutter, the weather's been poor the last couple of days so you get the reloading bench photos.

Will replace/ augment the album with outdoor photos ASAP.

*Small chunk out of lower buttstock, wrist in good shape (many of these are not). 
*Small crack in forearm was epoxy repaired and will not rebreak. 
*Action in great shape, I test fired it. It's 1903 vintage, however and like all guns over 100 years of age you should have it checked by a competent gunsmith YOU trust before firing - you don't know me from Adam!
*Still short chambered for older paper shells (see below). 
*I didn't "slick up" the action, but I did smooth it out with a detailed cleaning and gross de-burring. It's not a race-ready competition gun, but it's mighty nice (for a model 97...)
*Takedown frontend serial numbers match receiver. Plenty of adjustment left on the barrel lug. Takedown fit is nice and tight. Serial range: 200,xxx
*Receiver custom engraved E.J (or G.) Babcock - unknown history.
*Very nice patia and moderate finish left (see pictures).
*Full 30" unmolested original barrel - full fixed choke.

If the buyer desires I can lengthen the forcing cone to ease shooting modern loads, no charge.
If buyer desires I can cut-down (to 20") and convert to trench gun clone (at additional cost) 
If buyer desires I can retro fit for removable chokes (at additional cost)

While this is sold as a bonafide working gun, it's your responsibility to ensure it's checked out and in safe working order before you use it with safe loads.

Asking $400 for an honest-to goodness Winchester piece of great American history!
FTF to MD resident, will require a bill of sale or shipping on your dime to FFL (Dealer or C&R).
